   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>All for
                           Love</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>All for Love</title>; or, the World Well Lost; A
                              Tragedy, In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">John
                                 Dryden</ref>. As Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The
                              British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the
                              Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>,
                                 <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and
                                 <ref target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under
                              the Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical
                              and Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. VI. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Rule a Wife and Have a Wife</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Chances</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>New Way
                              to Pay Old Debts</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#AlexandertheGreat">Alexander the
                              Great</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>All for
                              Love</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged at the
                           <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref>
                        likely in July of 1677. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay
                        for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note></title>
                  <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>It is no slight honour to this play, that it was written by the illustrious author of
               the "<title>Ode on <ref target="people.html#CeciliaSt">St. Cecilia</ref>'s
                  Day</title>."<note><ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> refers to
                     <ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">John Dryden</ref>'s 1687 ode, "<title>A
                     Song for <ref target="people.html#CeciliaSt">St. Cecilia</ref>'s
                  Day</title>."</note> The play, in return, confers but little honour upon <ref
                  target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>.</p>

            <p>The burning bosom, throbbing heart, the enchanting sensations, which the author, in
               his odes and poems, inspires, are rarely excited by his dramatic works. The stage,
               which exalts the muse of many an author, humbles that of the present great poet; and
               he ranks as a dramatist beneath those rivals who can move the passions by a more
               judicious adherence to nature and simplicity.</p>

            <p>"<title>All for Love</title>" was the author's favourite drama;&#8212;he said, he
               wrote it solely to please himself, and had succeeded in his design. Yet, were it not
               for the interest which attaches to the names of his hero and heroine, their
               characters are too feebly drawn to produce those emotions which an audience at a
               tragedy come prepared to feel.</p>

            <p>Who can be inattentive to the loves of <ref target="people.html#AntoniusMarcus">Marc
                  Antony</ref> and <ref target="people.html#CleopatraVIIQueenofEgypt"
                  >Cleopatra</ref>? Yet, thus described, their fate in representation seldom draws a
               tear, or gives rise to one transport of passion in the breast of the most observing
               auditor. The work is, nevertheless, highly valuable. It is one of the most
               interesting parts <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>of
               Roman and Egyptian history; and the historian&#8212;<ref
                  target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>.</p>

            <p>There is certainly in this short history, compared with more copious ones, a
               diminution of <ref target="people.html#CleopatraVIIQueenofEgypt">Cleopatra</ref>'s
               faults: yet her character is by no means so graced with virtues, and dignified by
               heroism in this drama, as in the tragedy of <ref target="people.html#PompeytheGreat"
                  >Pompée</ref>, by the great <ref target="people.html#CorneillePierre"
                  >Corneille</ref>.<note><ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> refers
                  to <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Death of <ref
                           target="people.html#PompeytheGreat">Pompey</ref></title></hi> (<hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>La Mort de <ref target="people.html#PompeytheGreat"
                           >Pompée</ref></title></hi>) (1642) by <ref
                     target="people.html#CorneillePierre">Pierre Corneille</ref>.</note></p>

            <p>The wife of <ref target="people.html#AntoniusMarcus">Antony</ref>, in the present
               composition, is, unexpectedly, the most affecting personage in the whole piece: and
               the comic sentences of <ref target="people.html#Ventidius">Ventidius</ref> the sole
               support of those scenes, where the tragic parts, more particularly, decline into
               languor.</p>

            <p>The author was an advocate for tragi-comedy, and held, that all theatrical
               productions required alternate scenes of grief and joy, to render the whole a more
               perfect picture of nature, than could be given by one continued view of either. Some
               of his biographers have said, that, in his latter days, <ref
                  target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> altered this opinion, and was
               convinced, that tragedy and comedy should never unite.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Of Dramatick Poesie</title></hi> (1688) supports the genre of the
                  tragicomedy, while the preface to his translation of <ref
                     target="people.html#DufresnoyCharles">C.A. Du Fresnoy</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>De Arte Graphica</title></hi> (<hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Art of Painting</title></hi>) (1695) denounces
                  the concept.</note> It is probable he recanted; and it is consolatory to reflect,
               that this great man was as apt perhaps to change his mind upon all other subjects, as
               upon that in which his political interest was concerned.</p>

            <p>In politics, the author of this tragedy was so inconstant, that he wrote funeral
               lamentations on the death of <ref target="people.html#CromwellOliver">Oliver
                  Cromwell</ref>, and hymns of joy on the restoration of <ref
                  target="people.html#CharlesIKingofEngland">King Charles</ref>.</p>

            <p>He wrote "<title>The Spanish Friar</title>," to vilify the Roman Catholic religion,
               whilst that religion was persecuted; and translated an ancient Father, to prove it
               the true <pb n="5"/>faith, when the <ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland"
                  >King</ref> on the throne professed himself one of its members.<note>After working
                  for <ref target="people.html#CromwellOliver">Oliver Cromwell</ref>'s Secretary of
                  State under the Puritan Protectorate and, after <ref
                     target="people.html#CromwellOliver">Cromwell</ref>'s death in 1558, publishing
                  his "<title>Heroic Stanzas</title>" (1659), a eulogy on the life of <ref
                     target="people.html#CromwellOliver">Cromwell</ref>, <ref
                     target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> celebrated the subsequent
                  restoration of the monarchy in 1660 with his <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Astraea Redux</title></hi> when <ref
                     target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">Charles II </ref>assumed the
                  throne. <ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> then converted from
                  Anglicanism to Catholicism on the accession of <ref
                     target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James II</ref> and apparently
                  remained a Jacobite thereafter. Inchbald refers to <ref
                     target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>'s 1690 translation of <ref
                     target="people.html#MaurusRabanus">Rabanus Maurus</ref>, his <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Creator Spirit</title></hi>.</note></p>

            <p>This extraordinary man was a grandson of <ref target="people.html#DrydenErasmus">Sir
                  Erasmus Dryden</ref>, of Northamptonshire, and born near Oundle,<note>Oundle is a
                  market town and civil parish in North Northamptonshire.</note> in that county. His
               hereditary income seems to have been extremely confined, yet he was educated for no
                     profession;<note><ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>'s father
                  died in 1654, leaving him a piece of land which generated a small income, but not
                  enough to live on. <ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> was educated
                  at Westminster School in London and Trinity College at Cambridge, obtaining his
                  Bachelor of Arts degree from the latter in 1654.</note> whilst the emoluments of a
               poet, like those of a soldier, scarcely ever supply the various necessities of the
               gentleman.</p>

            <p>He married Lady C. Howard,<note><ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>
                  married Lady Elizabeth Howard (c. 1638–1714) in 1663.</note> sister to the <ref
                  target="people.html#HowardCharles">Earl of Berkshire</ref>; but this union could
               not give much aid to his finances, as it is testified, that the world has been
               indebted for his works to his poverty. His pen was not more pre-eminent than
               reluctant.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>'s manners were meek and modest in
               the same remarkable degree as his satire on his enemies was bold and revengeful; for,
               like other able writers of his time, his days were embittered by the envy and
               malignity of rivals.</p>

            <p>But with all their slander, and all his own in return, he was not so worn by evil
               passions as to die much before the age of seventy. He departed this life in the year
               1701, at his house in Gerrard Street, professing the faith of the Church of
                     Rome.<note><ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> died in poverty in
                  his home on Gerrard Street, London, in 1700.</note></p>

            <p>So distinguished a believer might have done honour to that Church&#8212;but <ref
                  target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> believed also in astrology.<note>From
                  his first poem "<title>Upon the death of the Lord Hastings</title>," an elegy for
                  a classmate taken by smallpox, in 1649 to his adaptation of <ref
                     target="people.html#ChaucerGeoffrey">Chaucer</ref>'s "<title>The Knight's
                     Tale</title>" in 1700, Dryden made consistent allusions to judicial astrology.
                  Judicial astrology was practice of predicting events through the calculation of
                  stellar and planetary bodies and their proximity to the Earth.</note></p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
